    "text_1": {
      "type": "content-block",
      "blocks": {
        "heading_1": {
          "type": "heading",
          "settings": {
            "text": "Introducing Walker Golf things",
            "tag": "h2",
            "size": "h3",
            "font": "serif"
          }
        },
        "text_1": {
          "type": "text",
          "settings": {
            "text": "<p>Before he was designing golf apparel, Jack Fardell was skating the streets of San Francisco, New York, and Sydney, racking up footage, magazine covers, and global sponsors. Now, the pro skater turned creative has teamed up with longtime friends from Adidas, Volcom, and Nike to build something new: a golf brand that doesn't feel like every other golf brand.</p><p>\u201cWe just wanted to make stuff we actually wanted to wear,\u201d Jack says. \u201cAnd we wanted to bring our friends along for the ride.\u201d</p><p>That spirit is the foundation of Walker Golf, a brand rooted in Australian golf culture, shaped by street and skate influence, and defined by technical, easygoing design. It's gear that feels as good off the course as it does on it.</p><p>What started as an idea for a skate brand evolved into something bigger, something that captures the laid-back energy of coastal Australia and blends it with a lifelong love of the game. Three years ago, the crew launched Walker Golf out of the Gold Coast with a simple goal: to make golf clothes that look good, feel good, and work wherever the day leads.</p><p>From the fairway to the skatepark to the pub, this is performance gear without the performance complex. Designed by people who play, made for people who live.</p>"
          }
        }
      },
      "block_order": ["heading_1", "text_1"],
